{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657141"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:23:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:23:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19108"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19108"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81547"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11842"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19108"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66897"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"8969"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27804"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27877"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81547"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient is about to have a chest X-ray and wants to know how much radiation this will expose him to. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the approximate effective radiation dose from a single posterior-anterior chest X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0.01 millisieverts","0.05 millisieverts","0.1 millisieverts","0.5 millisieverts","1.0 millisieverts"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding radiation doses from medical imaging is important for both healthcare workers and patients. A \u003Cstrong\u003E0.1 millisieverts\u003C/strong\u003E dose from a single chest X-ray is equivalent to about 10 days of natural background radiation exposure. The average person receives approximately 0.01 millisieverts per day from natural background radiation from cosmic rays, soil, building materials, and food. This equates to approximately 2.0 millisieverts per year.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.01 millisieverts\u003C/strong\u003E would be too low and represents approximately one day of background radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.05 millisieverts\u003C/strong\u003E represents about 5 days of background radiation exposure, which is less than the dose from a chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.5 millisieverts\u003C/strong\u003E is approximately the dose received from a lumbar spine X-ray, which is about 5 times higher than a chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1.0 millisieverts\u003C/strong\u003E represents half the average annual background radiation dose for most Australians. This is equivalent to about 10 chest X-rays.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor context, the dosages associated with other common radiological investigations include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT head 2 millisieverts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT chest 7 millisieverts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT abdomen/pelvis 10 millisieverts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese higher doses reflect the significantly greater radiation exposure from CT scanning compared to conventional radiography.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A single chest X-ray delivers approximately 0.1 millisieverts of radiation, equivalent to about 10 days of natural background radiation.","The average Australian receives approximately 1.5-2.0 millisieverts per year from natural background radiation.","Radiation workers in Australia are limited to 20 millisieverts per year averaged over five years."],"references":["Skinner, S. Radiation Safety, 2013, Australian Family Physician, https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/june/radiation-safety"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66897"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19108"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66897"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T10:58:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T10:59:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11842"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81547"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"item